        <abstract>
            <p>Surprising thought that diseases of plants should illustrate human pathology.</p>
            <p>Will recommend A. B. Frank’s article in a German encyclopedia, on diseases of plants, to Francis Darwin.</p>
            <p>Gives JP a good case of regeneration in plants – the radicle of the common bean. That plants have little power of regeneration is not difficult to understand by anyone who believes in Pangenesis, "if such a man exists … There is reason to think that my imaginary gemmules have small power of passing from cell to cell."</p>
            <p>Refers to early experiments in which he tried to produce galls in plants by injecting poisons.</p>
        </abstract>
